The paper deals with complexity results for justification logic, which is a subfield of mathematical logic. Therefore, cs.LO (Logic in Computer Science) is the most likely sub-category. The paper also involves complexity classes such as NEXP and Sigma 2 p, which are related to computational complexity theory, making cs.CC (Computational Complexity) and cs.AI (Artificial Intelligence) likely sub-categories as well. The paper also uses reduction techniques, which are common in algorithms and data structures, making cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms) a possible sub-category. Finally, the paper involves theoretical results that may have implications for machine learning and decision making, making cs.LG (Machine Learning) a less likely but still possible sub-category.
